To get straight to the point, this ice maker delivers on its promise to make small ice bullets within 9 minutes. In my initial test it made the first batch of cubes in about 9 minutes and 30 seconds, which is within the margin of error in my opinion. The machine itself isn't silent, but stays at a modest hum which shouldn't irritate anyone while it runs.

As long as you run the self-cleaning, and clean it a sufficient number of times on first use (seriously, go overkill with this if you want the ice cubes to taste proper), and plan to use the ice cubes promptly or otherwise put them in a freezer shortly after they are made, this machine will work fine. Where I feel this machine is lacking is in the details.

The ice cubes themselves are deposited into an ice cube tray at the front of the machine over the water reservoir. By design, this is one big chamber with water at the bottom, so it doesn't actually chill the entire chamber. If it did, the water would freeze at the bottom. This means the ice is free to start melting as soon as it's dropped into the tray. It will last a little while as new ice continues to cycle into the tray, but ultimately will wind up melting back into the reservoir, meaning that if you leave the ice maker running indefinitely, it just keeps refreezing the same water over and over again. This is extremely inefficient in my opinion.

I also really dislike the drain plug. It's a non-issue if you plan to freeze every last bit of water, but if there's anything to drain at the end, it is literally just a giant plug you pull out of the bottom. When I did this the water kind of went all over the place while I got the plug out of the way, and then it just drains rapidly as it's literally just a sizable hole--no slow drain mechanism or mini-pipe with a plug at the end, or anything really that would help you direct the water flow. Considering how easy it would have been to improve what I feel is a vital function for an appliance that potentially deals with a large amount of water if filled to the maximum level, this is a major detriment.

Overall, it DOES deliver on the "ice within 9 minutes" selling point, so I can only recommend this for occasions where you need a good deal of ice that will be used quickly. Since it can't maintain the ice it generates for an extended length of time, it's absolutely not a daily driver, or a replacement for a fridge with an ice maker built in. Please use that information to determine if this is the right machine for your needs.

I just purchased this machine recently because the laundromat is just getting too expensive and time consuming. I haven't used a laundromat in years and it's just not convenient when you have to let laundry pile up for a week or two! In-home laundry is much better but since I downsized to a cheaper apt I don't have machines. I used this little guy today for the first time and was pleased with the results. Of course the sink adapter leaked from my kitchen faucet but i'll play with it to see what helps. I only connected one water line to the cold intake because my faucet is a single piece design. I can control the temp of the water with the faucet. More importantly, the machine washed clothes nicely, didn't leak on my floor and wasn't noisy. The controls are a bit confusing but once you get the hang of it, it seems great. i tried the normal wash with some t-shirts and a couple towels and it became unbalanced during the spin. Easy fix but the clothes were sopping wet when i took them out, as if the water didn't spin out. Maybe the load was too small or the water level too high. I tried the cottons program on my second wash, filled the tub almost full of clothes and the clothes spun out nearly dry. They're on a rack in my bathroom right now. It'll be an experiment to see what settings work best. I have the machine on a small appliance dolly because it's a bit heavy, but it got wobbly when spinning so maybe i'll just deal with the tiny rollers on the bottom of the machine instead. Overall I'm really glad I purchased this machine, it holds more clothes than I anticipated. The laundromat will only be for big stuff like blankets or comforters now. Shipping was fast too! UPS brought it right to my door.

My Maytag oven stopped heating up. I could see the ignitor glowing but gas would not come on and ignite.
A quick search on the internet revealed that even though the ignitor was glowing, it can still be bad. I won't go into detail but basically the ignitor is electrically in line with the "safety" gas valve. If the ignitor completely fails, the gas valve will not open. However, as the ignitor ages it's electrical properties can change and while it glows it will not allow the gas valve to open. Apparently, gas valve failures are very rare but ignitor issues are common. Changing the ignitor (very easy to do) fixed my issue.

I bought this is a gift to my wife who puts ice in every drink she has, it was kinda of an impulse buy and now I don't regret it at all.  At first my wife was skeptical of it's awesomeness but within minutes we had ice and before we even realized we had a bucket full of ice.  You don't realize how nice it is to grab a shovel full of ice and walking away without having to refill an ice tray until it becomes a normal facet of life.  We rent an apartment and the fridge doesn't make ice so this is the next best thing to that.  It's larger then I pictured it but the convenience is amazing, I brought it to our holiday parties set it on the floor filled it up and let it make ice for us the whole time, it was a big hit.  Personally on a man level, I bought it because I know I can run this thing with my smaller inverter generator in my jeep which means I can bring it camping with me (please note if you tip it or shake it about a lot it's best to let it sit for 2 hours before operation), which equals free ice as long as I have a clean source of water, during Hurricane Sandy the fact that we had stored a ton of ice in our freezer kept all our food cold for the week or so we had no utility power.  It can be noisy when it's pulling water, I guess as noisy as a water pump can be, nothing unusual.  Sometimes when I'm napping the ice dropping in the basket kinda snaps me too, all these things are petty background noises I've quickly become accustomed to but I guess someone new to the ice maker should realize is part of the show.  Overall we are content with our purchase, now it needs to pass the test of time see how that goes.

First off, I had the panda washer and knew I wanted a panda dryer since I had such a great experience with it. The washer I have has a 10lb capacity and can fit a load directly from that to the dryer except for pants. This machine takes the same amount of electricity as my washer 850W which typically a dryer can take from 1800w-5000w, so if your thinking you can do a load of regular clothes in the typical 45min that a big washer does I think you need to bring down your expectations. If you want to dry quicker I recommend you get a more powerful dryer though it'll probably cost you a good $100 more and will sort you more on your monthly bills. As well as the size of dryer based of in person measurements are 23 1/2 tall 19 1/2 in wide 13 in depth. Inside the drum is 9 1/2 inches deep. As for nosie level it is very quiet that I don't even hear it running till I hear some buttons clank around the drum. In the manual they say it takes typically 1hr for clothing to dry on high heat on the hottest setting or 100min on the medium heat setting. I personally always have the button down for high and use the hottest setting(the red bar) and time myself for 30min, once the timers up I'll take out the clothes and whip them out straight and flip them inside out or right-side out and set another 25min. (Very important to flip them because it can drop the drying time by like 20min) I can wash 3 thick work pants with a pair of socks and undies and drying time takes about 1hr 25min or so on high/hot heat. But that is some really thick material. As for rags they take like 20-25min on high/hot. Shirts take 45min on high/hot. As for blankets I can fit a full bead spead with 3 pillow cases minus the comforter in and dry in about 30 to 45min so long as I whip them out and flip them halfway through on high/hot. Now for regular everyday jeans it take about 1hr and 5 to 10min to dry on high/hot. I personally wanted the smallest dryer I could find since I'm limited in space. And I wanted something that can take the amount of clothing my washer washes and so this fit all my needs. Plus, it came as a vent kit combo so I liked that I wouldn't have to spend money separately for that. But if your washer takes more than 10lb of clothes you might want to get a bigger dryer. Or if you want it to dry sooner than an hour than maybe one that is more powerful than 850w. But from the perspective that most big 1800w+ dryers take 45min to dry and this is only 850w I feel like it's amazing so long as you realize what you are buying. Also an important thing to note is that I realized the white felt like bit in the filter does need to be cleaned as well as with the filter for consistent heating I use a lint roller to clean it. Also I tried using 2 dryer balls to reduce heating time but only later learned 3 to 4 are recommended for small to medium loads and now see about 20min shaved off the drying time.

For AeroPress coffee enthusiasts who seek an eco-friendly and cost-effective alternative to paper filters, The MESH Reusable Metal Filter is a game-changer. Designed specifically for AeroPress coffee makers, including AeroPress Go, this innovative filter eliminates the need for disposable paper filters, resulting in a sustainable and convenient brewing experience. In this comprehensive review, we will explore the features and benefits of The MESH Reusable Metal Filter and how it enhances your AeroPress coffee brewing without compromising on flavor or convenience.

Eco-Friendly and Sustainable Brewing

The MESH Reusable Metal Filter offers a sustainable solution for AeroPress coffee brewing. By eliminating the need for paper filters, you significantly reduce waste and contribute to a greener environment. The metal filter is designed to be long-lasting, allowing you to enjoy countless cups of coffee without constantly disposing of paper filters. Embrace a more eco-friendly brewing routine with The MESH and enjoy guilt-free coffee.

Enhanced Flavor and Oils Retention

One of the notable advantages of The MESH Reusable Metal Filter is its ability to allow more oils and fine particles to pass through during the brewing process. This results in a fuller-bodied and more aromatic cup of coffee. The metal filter provides a richer flavor profile, allowing you to savor the nuances and complexities of your coffee beans. Say goodbye to paper filters that can potentially absorb some of the coffee's oils and taste the true essence of your coffee with The MESH.

Perfect Fit for AeroPress and AeroPress Go

The MESH Reusable Metal Filter is specifically designed to fit the AeroPress coffee maker, as well as the AeroPress Go coffee press. It seamlessly replaces the need for paper filters, providing a snug fit that ensures optimal brewing performance. The filter's fine mesh pattern effectively traps coffee grounds while allowing water to flow through smoothly, resulting in a clean and consistent brew every time. The perfect fit and functionality of The MESH make it an essential accessory for AeroPress coffee enthusiasts.

Easy to Use and Clean

Using The MESH Reusable Metal Filter is simple and hassle-free. Just insert it into your AeroPress coffee maker like you would with a paper filter, add your desired amount of coffee grounds, and proceed with your regular brewing process. After use, the filter can be easily rinsed under water or cleaned with a gentle brush. Its durable stainless steel construction ensures long-term usability and easy maintenance.

Conclusion

The MESH Reusable Metal Filter is a game-changer for AeroPress coffee brewing. With its eco-friendly design, enhanced flavor retention, perfect fit for AeroPress and AeroPress Go, and easy-to-use and clean features, this filter elevates your coffee brewing experience. Say goodbye to paper filters and embrace sustainability and convenience with The MESH. Enhance the flavor of your AeroPress coffee and enjoy a more eco-friendly brewing routine.

I have a front loader Samsung HE machine and that thing was dancing across the floor no matter what I tried. Finally I saw these feet on the "This Old House" program. What a blessing.  I was by myself a retired lady now, and I got 2 short 2 x 4 boards, placed one on top of the other, pulled that washer out from the wall, and it went forward with a push on the backside near the top, and I slid the boards under the back. Placed the feet where I guessed it would set back down. Had a small magnetized level on top and bingo.  Pushed the washer back to the wall. Opened the washer door and lifted up the machine with both arms from the opening, then with my foot, I pushed the 2 boards under neath the washer in the front. Set the pads down, pulled out the boards, bingo. All level. Have done 3 loads tonight and not a peep from the walking machine. Smooth like butter.  Woo Hoo.  I took the 2 old rubber feet off the back, but the front ones didn't budge so I left them on, just screwed the feet in tighter in the front to compensate for the height.

The Nina Soft spin dryer is made in Brazil by an outfit called Mueller.

It seems to do a good job, but I have no other spin dryers with which to compare it. I would have liked to have tried the original model that Laundry alternative imported. I actually wanted to get the less expensive "[[ASIN:B002HT0958 Mini Countertop Spin Dryer Clothes Spin Dryer Portable Clothes Dryer]]" which I think has less capacity than the Nina Soft, but is less than 1/2 the cost of the Nina Soft. The Mini Counter-top Dryer also has a built-in timer (with the Nina Soft lacks). Unfortunately, Laundry Alternative wasn't shipping the counter-top model when I needed a spin dryer (evidently due to some QC issue).

At any rate, there is somewhat of a technique to balancing and positioning the clothes for optimal spinning and drying. An unbalanced (or excessive) load of clothes could cause the drum to wobble excessively (which could damage the unit) and never get up to speed.

Essentially, try to keep the clothes along the wall of the "drum," with the heaviest articles of clothing on bottom and the lighter clothes on top. Try to spread the clothes as flatly and as neatly as is reasonable (areas of the clothes that are thickly "bunched-up" along the wall tend to remain more damp after the spin). The clothes should form a tube up the wall with a hollow center. Folding the clothes into a strip helps avoid bunching-up. Also, try to balance the articles on opposite sides of the drum (put one sock opposite another sock, etc.).

In addition, if you place a wringed-out article of clothing on one side of the drum, wring-out the article on the opposite side (sopping wet clothes on one side can cause wobble).

I have found that only one or two heavy pieces are possible in the Nina Soft for it to start spinning without violent wobble.

I have also discovered a special trick to balance denim jeans -- put the seat section on the center bottom of the drum, and spiral the pant legs up the sides of the drum. Then, without adding any more clothes, spin the pair of jeans alone (with the "protective disk," of course) for about twenty seconds to get rid of the excess water. Then, stop the spin and shove the seat of the jeans along one wall and add more clothes, with care to add a little more weight to the side opposite the jeans seat. Then, spin as usual.

It's too bad that Mueller didn't include a manual power switch (or a timer). The instructions actually have one plugging the unit into the wall socket with the lid closed, which starts the spin. However, such a procedure could cause mild arcing at the wall plug, which isn't too great. I have a short extension cord with an in-line switch, and it works well. Of course, when the lid is opened during the spin, the Nina Soft's internal switch cuts the power to the spin motor, and when the lid is further opened, a friction strap brake closes around a flywheel to stop the drum from spinning. I flip the switch on my cable and let the motor spin down a little before I open the lid, to save the brake.

One more thing, the water sprays wide out of the nozzle and off to one side a little. So, get a wide, round, plastic bowl or shallow tub to catch the water.

I bought these replacement charcoal filters for our Cuisinart coffee maker. Reviews for the coffee maker raved about how the filters make a difference and help you start with good water to get good taste. We had a Braun coffee maker for decades with no filters and we have hard water, and I don't taste any noticeable difference now with filters, so I can't rave, but they are not very expensive and certainly can't hurt.

Charcoal should take out off-odors, some impurities, etc., but I don't know the efficiency of these little filters. I suspect that when the filters that come with the coffee maker reach their end, you could just take them out (don't leave them there forever, they could eventually leak charcoal dust into the coffee which would be annoying, or maybe get moldy) and run it without any filter cartridges at all, but again, they probably help some and can't hurt and they are not expensive.

They make a more noticeable difference if you have water with odors (sulfur, etc.) than they do with mine. Meanwhile, I bought a year's supply of replacements to enable Amazon free shipping, which further reduces the cost.

As other reviewers have noted, this filter does not have sufficient capacity for many 10-12 cup percolators. It would be nice if they offered more than one size.

Also, I find that I have had to increase the amount of coffee I use in my percolator (an old Corningware 10-cup model)to get the right strength--I think it's because the filter is so small in diameter that some of the water misses the basket entirely during the perking process (Pouring a half a cup of the just-perked coffee back through the grounds creates a stronger brew, but who wants to do that every time?). People with other makes of percolators may not experience this problem. If I could control the length of the perking cycle this problem might be resolved, but I can't. With coffee so expensive, it's aggravating to have to use more!

I used to have a wonderful old percolator (I think it was a Presto)that had both a fine in-spout strainer and an adjustable strength setting. It kept the grounds out of my coffee and I could control the length of the perking cycle. I wish they still made it, because it made perfect coffee with any grind.

I'm very pleased with this fan, but I had to reverse the direction. My old Nutone vent hood contained a fan that mounted with the motor below the fan blade, and looked almost the same as this one. However, out of the box, this fan is wired to be mounted with the fan on the underside and the motor on the top. In my installation, the fan was upside down, blowing instead of sucking.

To reverse the direction, you have to unscrew the two screws on the end of the motor, pull off the bearing cover, then flip over the magnet (see photo). Screw it all back together, and the motor will spin in the opposite direction. It took me about five minutes. Search youtube for Yb_k6gxNej0 and you will find the howto video that I followed to make this happen.

I read all the bad reviews but was interested to check this product out anyway.  I bought them to use with the Hamilton Beach 12-Cup Coffee Maker (49467) that I recently purchased.  Well, everything bad that I read about these filters and the design of their use is true.  The filters themselves don't stay in their little basket, they float up.  That's even after soaking them the recommended amount of time and after several pots of coffee.  The little basket they are supposed to fit in in nearly impossible to insert at the bottom of the reservoir for this model, and the tools that came with the filters are all but useless.  Also, no instructions came with them.  The reservoir is so narrow that in trying to insert the plastic basket by hand, I scraped the back of my hand several times.  Not worth the blood and aggravation!  Also, yes the basket does not sit tight in the hole where it goes, so water passes around the basket instead of through the filter.  Basic hydraulics indicate that water will flow in the direction of least resistance, so most of the water probably doesn't even go through the filter. The design could have been so much better.

My side by side fridge stopped cooling and was getting warm, fan and compressor on backside bottom of fridge were both working fine... the fan above the evaporator coils (inside the freezer panels) was not turning and had ice buildup on coils, disconnected thermostat wire from the fan, used a jump wire to ground out that one terminal to the fan and it started working. That was enough to keep fridge cool until I received the replacement thermostat. Thermostat is mounted on the coils near the top right just below the fan motor, it's held on with a clip and can be easily removed. Two days later I got the replacement, one of the connectors went through the back of the fridge and is hooked up to NOTHING, probably a service port or something. Instead I just cut the wire on the inside and connected the new wire to it with a screw-on wire connector, hooked it up... fan didn't turn on right away but after a few minutes it worked! Let it run overnight just to make sure before I put all panels back together. Tucked wires back in place and secured with new supplied tie-wrap. All good!

This is the second stainless steel filter I have used. I use paper filters with both of these steel filters. I feel the coffee's flavor is better when this product is used than my first filter. This filter is easier to clean and use than my first one with the plastic diffuser on the top. I believe this filter produces better results due to the lack of drains on the sides of the body. This forces the brewing water to flow through a single path top to bottom through the depth of the coffee grounds and not through side drains of my previous model. I believe this is closer to the way water flows through a one shot K-Cup cartridge and therefore produces a better robust flavor. The only issue I have encountered is an occasional drip from lid fill hole or rim. This may be due to my use of a paper filter with this product and is also present in my first steel filter.

(Update)
I've been using this product for a while now and I am still getting good results consistently with it. It appears to be more tolerant of my high filling of the "Simple Cups" paper filters I use with this. I did not even notice the one time a paper filter "blew out" because the grounds were well contained within the bottom of the stainless steel filter. I am still convinced that my "Fill N'Save Elite Series Stainless Steel" filter is an improvement to my previous stainless steel filter. [[VIDEOID:3d11ef082b215ecb42060e81ef757aa2]] Let's start by saying this isn't advertised as a $500.00 washing machine. It is in the $20 range and for me, worth it. They describe it as a "dishwasher and washing machine." I've used several items like this or very similar. This one seems fairly sturdy and functions as described (I've used this one once so far.) I've used these types of washing items for washing small, lightweight clothing as well as similar item to wash dishes. For small lightweight clothing it functions the way a standard washing machine does as it agitates the clothing and water. The difference is that you have to do the rest such as rinsing and wringing out.
This item has several modes. Automatic (goes through all cycles), agitate only, (rotates), ultrasonic vibration only (used in some dishwashing items) and bubbles only.
For small lightweight clothing, the agitating works great. When I use as a dishwasher, I sometimes use automatic (but since it doesn't have a fan guard, sometimes the dishes bump into the rotation.) I also use the ultrasonic vibration alone for dish washing with soapy water. While this doesn't clean like a standard dishwashing unit costing hundreds of dollars, I think of it like I'm soaking the dishes in a "super soaking" mode. This allows me time to do other things in the kitchen while the dishes are getting fairly clean. I've also noticed similar items that are advertised as "portable sink dishwashers" that only have the ultrasonic vibration feature and sells for more than double. So for me, this is fairly priced and seems to do a decent job.

I've had this range for about 2 years. My kitchen only has space for a 20" range, and this matched my other black/stainless appliances. I'm giving it two stars because the oven, and all the burners, are still working (see UPDATE). Otherwise, here's my experience... This is not a good stove for people who like to cook and bake. It is very cheaply made, light, and flimsy. It can't take constant cleaning. It seems more appropriate for heating pre-made foods. Wiping the stove down with kitchen spray cleaner has resulted in all the numbers around the dials wearing off. I now have to use an oven thermometer to set the proper temperature to bake. The oven arrived with a gasket to seal the oven door. That burned up the first time I baked. Although I keep a foil pan at the bottom of the oven to catch spills, and clean my oven monthly, the panel that makes up the floor of the oven has rusted. I noticed visible drip stains behind the glass of the oven door. There's a small glass panel, held by 2 screws and metal washers on the interior of the door. I removed that, cleaned it, reinstalled it, and still saw the stains. Came to find there is a gap between the top of the door and the door glass, that will catch anything that spills from the stove top. Cleaning it requires dismantling the entire oven door. Nothing sits level on this stove. I ended up putting a metal "stand" under the center of the 'far too thin stove top to support pots and keep them from sloping down. I'm not sure what grade of stainless steel the stove top is supposed to be, but my stove top developed rust stains. I have to sand it with emery cloth to keep it from looking like I have burnt grease on it. On a more positive note, it does look nice when it's clean and as I said earlier, the oven and burners all still work. Unfortunately, I wouldn't recommend this range.

UPDATE: 10/02/2018: AS of now, I have one burner not working. The oven door will no longer stay closed on it's own and requires I prop something in front of it while baking/broiling. When I think that I replaced a stove that was almost 50 years old, with one that couldn't last 5, I know this stove is really a piece of.... well... just look for something else. I feel like, for the price, I leased a crappy stove for a couple of years, and have to go look for a new one. Not the way to buy major appliances. Resist any temptation to purchase this stove. You'll definitely end up regretting it.
